Wayne Gretzky:
	1) Wayne won four Stanley Cup championships with the Edmonton Oilers (1984-1985, 1987-1988).
	2) Gretzky was the only player to have his jersey number (No. 99) retired by the National Hockey League.
	3) Wayne made a cameo on the soap opera, "The Young and the Restless," in 1981.
Bobby Orr:
	1) At the age of fourteen the Boston Bruins signed Bobby Orr into their organization for $2,800.
	2) Bobby Orr is most commonly recognized by the famous scene, dubbed "The Goal", in which Orr is seen flying through the air in front of the St. Louis Blues net after scoring the game-winning goal to make the Bruins Stanley Cup Champions (after a 29 year drought).
	3)  Bobby Orr holds the record for most points and assists in a single season by a defenceman.
Mario Lemieux:
	1) Lemieux is widely acknowledged to be one of the best players of all time and has been dubbed "The Magnificent One", "Le Magnifique" and who could forget "Super Mario"!
	2) Lemieux led Team Canada to an Olympic gold medal in 2002, a championship at the 2004 World Cup of Hockey, and a Canada Cup in 1987.
	3) Lemieux's career was plagued by health problems that included spinal disc herniation, Hodgkin's lymphoma, chronic tendinitis of a hip-flexor muscle, and chronic back pain so severe that other people had to tie his skates.
Gordie Howe:
	1) Gordie Howe was affectionately known by fans and players as "Mr. Hockey".
	2) Although he only achieved the feat twice in his own career, he became the namesake of the "Gordie Howe hat trick": a goal, an assist, and a fight in the same game.
	3) Gordie Howe played 26 seasons in the NHL, from 1946 to 1980, a record that remains to be broken.
Sidney Crosby:
	1) Nicknamed "The Next One", Crosby was one of the most highly regarded draft picks in hockey history.
	2) Crosby became the youngest captain in NHL history to win the Stanley Cup in the 2008-09 season when the Pittsburgh Penguins defeated the Detroit Red Wings in seven games.
	3) Crosby is a member of the elite "Triple Gold Club", which is a club of hockey players and coaches who have won an Olympic Games gold medal, a World Championship gold medal, and the Stanley Cup.
Alexander Ovechkin:
	1) Ovechkin has led the NHL in goal scoring, and won the Rocket Richard Trophy, six times in his career. 
	2) Ovechkin has represented Russia at eleven World Championships and three Olympics in his career, winning the World Championship three times.
	3) Ovechkin scored a goal that many consider one of the greatest goals of all time. Knocked down by and sliding on his back facing away from the net, Ovechkin was able to hook the puck with one hand on his stick and slide it into the net past goalie Brian Boucher for his second goal of the night.
Steve Yzerman:
	1) Stevey finished his career ranked as the seventh all-time leading scorer in NHL history, having scored a career-high 155 points (65 goals and 90 assists) in 1988–89.
	2) at the age of 21, Yzerman was named captain of the Red Wings and continuously served for the next two decades, retiring as the longest-serving captain of any team in North American major league sports history.
	3) Yzerman is the current general manager of the Tampa Bay Lightning.
Jaromir Jagr:
	1) Jagr is the leading point scorer among active NHL players and has the second most points in NHL history.
	2) For two decades, from 1981 to 2001, only three players won the Art Ross Trophy as the leading point-scorer over the regular season: Wayne Gretzky, Mario Lemieux and Jágr.
	3) Jagr is also one of only 27 hockey players in the Triple Gold Club, individuals who have played for teams that have won the Stanley Cup (1991, 1992), the Ice Hockey World Championships (2005, 2010) and the Olympic gold medal in ice hockey (1998).
Eric Lindros:
	1) Internationally, Lindros represented Canada at the World Junior Championships three times (1990, 1991 and 1992), winning gold medals in 1990 and 1991.
	2) Lindros was chosen first overall in the 1991 NHL Entry Draft by the Quebec Nordiques. He refused to play for the Nordiques and was eventually traded to the Philadelphia Flyers in 1992.
	3) Lindros' hard-nosed style caused him to miss significant time with injuries, and he had many problems with concussions. He is known for getting absolutely rocked by Scott Stevens (Devils) in game 7 of the 3rd round of the 1999-00 playoffs.
Mats Sundin:
	1) Originally drafted first overall in 1989, Sundin played his first four seasons in the NHL with the Quebec Nordiques before being traded to the Maple Leafs, where he remained for the majority of his career.
	2) Apart from two seasons, Sundin scored at least 70 points in every season of his career, played at least 70 games in every season and led the Maple Leafs in points nearly every year he was with the team.
	3) Internationally, Sundin won three gold medals with Sweden at the World Championships and a gold medal at the 2006 Winter Olympics in Turin.
Guy Lafleur:
	1) Lafleur is a Canadian former professional ice hockey player who was the first player in the NHL to score 50 goals and 100 points in six straight seasons.
	2) Lafleur played for the Montreal Canadiens, New York Rangers and Quebec Nordiques in an NHL career spanning 17 seasons, and five Stanley Cup championships.
	3) During the 1978 Stanley Cup finals, Boston Bruins Head Coach Don Cherry ordered his players to put their sticks up and hit Lafleur whenever they encountered him. At the end of the series, Lafleur's head was swathed in bandages after numerous slashes from Bruin players.
Carey Price:
	1) In 2015, Price was the winner of the Ted Lindsay, Jennings, Vezina and Hart trophies, becoming the first goaltender in NHL history to win all four individual awards in the same season.
	2) Price won a gold medal at the 2007 World Junior Ice Hockey Championships in Sweden.
	3) Price is widely considered as one of the best goaltenders in the world.
Mark Messier:
	1) Messier played a quarter of a century in the NHL (1979–2004) with the Edmonton Oilers, New York Rangers, and Vancouver Canucks.
	2) Messier is second on the all-time career lists for playoff points (295) and regular season games played (1756), and is third for regular season points (1887).
	3) Messier is a six-time Stanley Cup champion - five with the Oilers and one with the Rangers, and is the only player to captain two different professional teams to championships.
Evgeni Malkin:
	1) Malkin, also known as 'Gino', is a Russian professional ice hockey center and alternate captain for the Pittsburgh Penguins of the NHL.
	2) After his first season with the Penguins Malkin was awarded the Calder Memorial Trophy as the NHL's best rookie.
	3) Malkin is the only Penguins player besides Mario Lemieux to win a Calder Memorial Trophy.